::: {.t .m0 .xa .h6 .y3a .ff1 .fs4 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
ABSTRACT
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y3b .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
A Register Transfer Level (RTL) design and verification of a[]{._ ._0}
full-duplex U[]{._ ._2}niversal Asynchronous
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y3c .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
Receiver/Transmitter (UART) system is presented, utilizing Verilog HDL.
The UART core is designed to
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y3d .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
enable reliable asynchronous serial data exchange, featuring standard 8
data bits, no parity, and 1 stop bit
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y3e .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
(8N1) framing. The system is engineered for operation at a 9600 baud
rate with a 50 MHz clock frequency,
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y3f .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
employing a robust \$16\\times\$ oversampling mechanism for the
receiver. Key modular components include
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y40 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
a highly accurate Baud Rate Generator, dedicated Transmitter a[]{._
._0}nd Receiver Finite State Machines (FSMs),
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y41 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
and dual FIFO buffers for efficient data flow management and decoupling
of clock domains.
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y42 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
Implementation, synthesis, and functional ver[]{._ ._0}ification were
conducted entirely within the Xilinx Vivado
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y43 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
environment, specifically targeting the Artix-7 FPGA architecture[]{._
._0} of the Basys3 board. Rigorous simula[]{._ ._2}tion
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y44 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
using a self-checking testbench confirmed the successful data transfer
and validated the design\'s structural
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y45 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
integrity, timing performance, and readiness for embedded system
integration.
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y46 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .h6 .y47 .ff1 .fs4 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
Introduction
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .h9 .y48 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
The Universal Asynchronous Receiver/Transmitter (UART)[ ]{.ff1}is a
foundational serial communication protocol
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y49 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
essential for robust data exchange in deeply embedded systems. I[]{._
._0}ts asynchronous nature is key; instead of
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y4a .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
sharing a clock signal, reliability is achieved by structuring the data
into precisely timed fr[]{._ ._0}am[]{._ ._2}es that include
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y4b .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
a Start bit, data payload, and Stop bit. This design leverages Verilog
HDL to implement the UART in
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .h9 .y4c .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
dedicated Register Transfer Level [(]{.ff1}RTL[) ]{.ff1 .ls1}logic,
taking full advantage of the Artix-7 FPGA architecture on
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y4d .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
the Basys3 board. Using an FPGA allows for highly parallel and
reconfigurable hardware, ensuring
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y4e .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
deterministic timing performance that software-based solutions cannot
match. The c[]{._ ._0}ore objective was to
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y4f .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
design a robust, full-duplex UART, realized as a modular system
incorporating a Baud Rate Generator,
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .h9 .y50 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
dedicated Transmitter (TX) and Receiver (RX) Finite State Machines
(FSMs)[, ]{.ff1}and First-In, First-Out (FIFO)
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y51 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
buffers for effective flow control and throughput management. The entire
design process, including
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y52 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
synthesis and verification, was executed within the
industry-[st]{.ls2}andard Xilinx Vivado environment.
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y53 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
The design adheres to strict technical specifications to guarantee
communication integrity across the serial
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y54 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
link. The system utilizes the FPGA\'s single 50 MHz system clock and is
configured for a standard 9600 bps
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y55 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
baud ra[te]{.ls3} using the ubiquitous 8N1 frame format (8 data bits, no
parity, 1 stop bit). A critical design feature
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y56 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
is the Receiver\'s employment of a 16\\times oversampling technique.
This method samples the incoming
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y57 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
serial data sixteen times per bit period, allowing the receiver to
accurately pinpoint the true center of the bit
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y58 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
and effectively mitigating the effects of c[]{._ ._0}lock skew, signal
jitter, and minor rate mismatches between the
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y59 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
transmitter and receiver. This required setting the Baud Rate
Generator\'s counter to 326 clock cycles.
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y5a .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
Furthermore, to prevent buffer overrun or underrun during potentially
unpredictable burst transfers, two
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y5b .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
independent 16-entry FIFO buffers were integrated for the TX and RX data
paths, fundamentally decoupling
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y5c .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
the slow, bit-by-bit serial transfer rate from the processor\'s faster
para[]{._ ._0}llel logic interface.[]{._ ._2}
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y5d .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .h6 .y5e .ff1 .fs4 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
A[RC]{.ls1}HITECTURE
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y5f .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
The overall architecture of the full-duplex UART system is modular,
built around a shared timing source[]{._ ._0}
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y60 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
and two independent data paths for transmission (TX) and rece[]{._
._0}ption (RX). []{._ ._2}The system begins with the Baud
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y61 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
Rate Generator, which receives the main system clock (clk) and produces
the pr[]{._ ._0}ecise S_tick signal needed
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y62 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
for 16times oversampling. This s_tick synchronizes both the Receiver and
the Transmitter cores. For the RX
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y63 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
path, incoming serial data (rx) is processed by the Receiver module,
which converts it to parallel data (dout /
:::
:::
:::

::: {.pi data-data="{\"ctm\":[1.500000,0.000000,0.000000,1.500000,0.000000,0.000000]}"}
:::
:::

::: {.c .x0 .y0 .w2 .h0}
::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y38 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
w_data) and writes it to the RX FIFO upon completion. For the TX[]{._
._0} path, the TX FIFO stores parallel data
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y64 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
(wr_data) supplied by the host. The Transmitter module reads data
(rd_data / din) from the TX FIFO when
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y65 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
the FIFO is not empty (empty is low), converts it into a serial
bitstream, and outputs it as tx. Both FIFOs
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y66 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
include full and empty flags to manage flow control between the internal
logic and the external interface.
:::

CODE:

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y6f .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls4 .ws0}
//////// [baud rate generator ]{.ls0}
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y70 .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
module baud_rate_gen (clk, rst, S_tick);
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y71 .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
[ ]{.ls5}parameter BAUD_RATE = 9600;
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y72 .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
[ ]{.ls5}parameter CLK_FREQ = 50000000;
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y73 .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls5 .ws0}
[input clk, rst; ]{.ls0}
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y74 .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
[ ]{.ls5}output reg S_tick;
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y75 .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls5 .ws0}
[// Calculate divider for 9600 baud at 50MHz ]{.ls0}
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y76 .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
[ ]{.ls5}// 50,000,000 / (9600 \* 16) = 325.52 ? 326
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y77 .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
[ ]{.ls5}localparam DIVIDER = 326;
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y78 .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
[ ]{.ls5}localparam COUNTER_WIDTH = \$clog2(DIVIDER);
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y79 .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls5 .ws0}
[re[g \[COUNTER_WIDTH-1:0\] counter = 0; ]{.ls0}]{.ls6}
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y7a .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
[ ]{.ls5}always @(posedge clk or posedge rst) begin
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y7b .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
[ ]{.ls5} if (rst) begin
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y7c .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
counter \<= 0;
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y7d .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
S_tick \<= 0;
:::
:::
:::

end else begin
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y7f .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
if (counter == DIVIDER - 1) begin
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y80 .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y93 .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}

:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y99 .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
end
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .hb .y9a .ff2 .fs7 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}

::: {.t .m0 .xa .h6 .yb8 .ff1 .fs4 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
RESULTS
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .yb9 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
The modular Verilog RTL code was implemented and synthesized using the
Xilinx Vivado deve[]{._ ._0}lopment
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .yba .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
suite, specifically targeting the Artix-7 FPGA architecture of the[]{._
._0} Basys3 board. The synthesis process
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .ybb .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
successfully mapped the entire digital core[---]{.ff7}including the Baud
Rate Generator, the dedicated TX/RX
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .ybc .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
Finite State Machines (FSMs), and the synchronous FIFO
buffers[---]{.ff7}into a highly optimized netlist. This
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .ybd .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
modular approach proved extremely effective in achieving a c[]{._
._0}ompact and efficient hardware footprint. The
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .ybe .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
total resource utilization confirmed the design\'s scalability and low
complexity, requiring only 200 Look-Up
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .ybf .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
Tables (LUTs) (0.15% of available logic) and 339 Flip-Flops (FFs) (0.13%
of available). This minimal
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .yc0 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
usage validates the design as suitable for integration into larger,
r[]{._ ._0}esource-constrained embedded systems.
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .yc1 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
Critical analysis of the synthesis and place-and-route timing report
confirmed that the design successfully
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .yc2 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
met all performance requirements relative to the 50 MHz system clock.
The analysis reported a Worst
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .yc3 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
Negative Slack (WNS) value of infinite (inf), indicating that the design
is exceptionally stable and free from
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .yc4 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
any setup or hold timing violations. This high timing margin is crucial
for reliable operation in hardware[]{._ ._0} a[]{._ ._2}nd
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .yc5 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
provides substantial resilience against clock jitter and exter[]{._
._0}nal variations. Furthermore, the power analysis
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .yc6 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
estimated a low Total On-Chip Power consumption of 7.031 W, with the
majority being dynamic power
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .yc7 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
related to switching activity.
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .yc8 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
Functional verification was conducted using a dedicated, self-checking
Verilog testbench (uart_tb.v), which
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .yc9 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
modeled a full-duplex, cross-communication scenario between two separate
instantiated UART cores
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .yca .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
(uart_A and uart_B). This rigorous environment allowed for the precise
observation of all internal timing
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .ycb .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
signals, FSM state transitions, and serial data flow. The simulation
verified two key transmission sequence[]{._ ._0}s:
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .ycc .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
first, uart_A successfully transmitted the data byte 0xAA to uart_B, and
second, uart_B successfully
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .ycd .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
transmitted 0x55 back to uart_A.
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .y27 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
In both test cases, the receiver\'s FIFO correc[]{._ ._0}tly captured
the expected data after the calculated transmission
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .yce .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
delay, confirming the functional accurac[]{._ ._0}y of every component.
This successfully validated the integrity of
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .ycf .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
the Baud Rate Generator\'s timing, the accurate bit-sampling of the
Receiver\'s \$16\\times\$ oversampling
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .yd0 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
logic, and the reliable state progre[]{._ ._0}ssion of both the TX and
RX FSMs throu[]{._ ._2}gh the Start, Data, and Stop bit
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .yd1 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
phases. The verification ensures that the designed UART core is robust
and ready for physical deployment
:::

::: {.t .m0 .xa .ha .yd2 .ff2 .fs6 .fc0 .sc0 .ls0 .ws0}
on the Artix-7 FPGA.
:::
